  "voiceover": "I'm going to read you a passage — guess the year it was written. He was despised and rejected by men, a man of sorrows, and acquainted with grief. But he was pierced for our transgressions, crushed for our iniquities; and by his wounds we are healed. Like a lamb led to the slaughter, he did not open his mouth. So what year? This is not the Gospels. It's Isaiah 53, written centuries before Jesus was born. And we can prove the date: the Dead Sea Scrolls gave us a complete copy of Isaiah from about 125 BC — over a century before Christ. No one edited it after the fact. Now go back to verse 5. This is the heart of it: he was not merely suffering. He was pierced for us. Wounded in our place. Verse 6: we all, like sheep, have gone astray — and the Lord has laid on him the iniquity of us all. And the apostle Peter quotes it straight back: he bore our sins in his body on the tree; by his wounds you have been healed. Even the small details fit — a criminal's death and a rich man's grave, Jesus crucified between thieves and buried by Joseph, a rich man. It isn't a mathematical proof. It's a portrait, sketched centuries early, that comes into focus on one face. Read Isaiah 53 for yourself. Coincidence, or providence? You decide.",
